worksheet.stem:
Use the model to predict the settling velocity of a 2500 kg/m3 density sphere. (Round the final answer to four decimal places.)

 

The setting velocity of a 2500 kg/m3 density sphere is __1__ × 10–3 m/s.
worksheet.commonFeedback:
The equation can be expressed as

 

%media:formula2.mml%

 

Thus, if we regress %media:formula3.mml% versus %media:formula4.mml%, the slope (with MATLAB) will be a1 = gd2/(18μ) and the intercept will be a2 = gρd2/(18μ).

Therefore,

 

%media:formula5.mml% and %media:formula6.mml%

 

Here is a MATLAB script to solve the problem and make the plot

 

clear,clc,clf
format compact;format short g
g=9.81;
rhos=[1500  1600  1700  1800  1900  2000  2100  2200  2300];
vterm=[1.03 1.12  1.59  1.76  2.42  2.51  3.06  3 3.5];
vterm=vterm*1e-3;
d=10e-6;
a=polyfit(rhos,vterm,1)
vinf=1000*(a(1)*rhos+a(2));
rhoplot=[min(rhos):max(rhos)];
vinfplot=1e3*(a(1)*rhoplot+a(2));
vterm=vterm*1e3;
plot(rhos,vterm,'o',rhoplot,vinfplot)
legend('data','best-fit line','location','best')
title('Plot of terminal velocity versus sphere density')
xlabel('rhos (kg/m3)'),ylabel('terminal velocity (10^-3 m/s)')
v2500=1e3*(a(1)*2500+a(2))
 

Output

 

a =
   3.2017e-06   -0.0038621
v2500 =
       4.1421

 

Therefore, the settling velocity of the 2500 kg/m3 sphere is estimated to be 4.1421 × 10–3 m/s.

worksheet.stem:
Use the linearized model to estimate k and c0 based on the following data. (Round the final answers to four decimal places.)

 

The value of k is __a__ L2/(mg2 d), and the value of c0 is __b__ mg/L.
worksheet.commonFeedback:
Here is a MATLAB script that solves the problem:

 

clear,clc,clf
format short g, format compact
t=[ 0 0.5 1 1.5 2 3 4 5];
c=[3.26 2.09  1.62  1.48  1.17  1.06  0.9 0.85];
% linear fit
y=1./c.^2;
a=polyfit(t,y,1)
% compute coefficients
k=a(1)/2
c0=sqrt(1/a(2))
% generate plots
tplot=0:max(t)/100:max(t);
cplot=a(1)*tplot+a(2);
subplot(2,1,1)
plot(t,y,'o',tplot,cplot)
title('linear transformed plot')
ylabel('1/c^2')
cplot=c0./sqrt(1+2*k*c0^2*tplot);
subplot(2,1,2)
plot(t,c,'o',tplot,cplot)
title('untransformed plot')
xlabel('t'),ylabel('c')

 

Output

 

a =
      0.26646      0.10875
k =
      0.13323
c0 =
       3.0324

sectionBreak.stem:
Consider the optimization techniques to find the optimal values of one- and multi-dimensional functions. Random numbers provide an alternative means to solve the same sorts of problems. This is done by repeatedly evaluating the function at randomly selected values of the independent variable and keeping track of the one that yields the best value of the function being optimized. If a sufficient number of samples are conducted, the optimum will eventually be located. In their simplest manifestations, such approaches are not very efficient. However, they do have the advantage that they can detect global optimums for functions with lots of local optima.

xopt=x(i);

sectionBreak.stem:
Suppose that a population of particles is confined to motion along a one-dimensional line (see the figure). Assume that each particle has an equal likelihood of moving a distance, Δx, to either the left or right over a time step, Δt. At t = 0 all particles are grouped at x = 0 and are allowed to take one step in either direction. After Δt, approximately 50% will step to the right and 50% to the left. After 2Δt, 25% would be two steps to the left, 25% would be two steps to the right, and 50% would have stepped back to the origin. With additional time, the particles would spread out with the population greater near the origin and diminishing at the ends. The net result is that the distribution of the particles approaches a spreading bell-shaped distribution. This process, formally called a random walk (or drunkard’s walk), describes many phenomena in engineering and science with a common example being Brownian motion.

 

%media:14.040.1.jpg%

sectionBreak.stem:
Suppose that a population of particles is confined to motion along a two-dimensional line (see the figure). Assume that each particle has an equal likelihood of moving a random step of length Δ at a random angle θ ranging from 0 to 2π. At θ = 0 all particles are grouped at origin and are allowed to take one step in either direction. After Δ, approximately 50% will step to the right and 50% to the left. After 2Δ, 25% would be two steps to the left, 25% would be two steps to the right, and 50% would have stepped back to the origin. With additional time, the particles would spread out with the population greater near the origin and diminishing at the ends. The net result is that the distribution of the particles approaches a spreading bell-shaped distribution. This process, formally called a random walk (or drunkard’s walk), describes many phenomena in engineering and science with a common example being Brownian motion.

 

%media:14.041.jpg%

worksheet.stem:
Use the power model to predict the record time for a half marathon (21,097.5 m). Note that the actual records for the half marathon are 3503 s (Tadese) and 3909 s (Kiplagat) for men and women, respectively. (Round the final answers to the nearest whole number.)

 

The record time for a half marathon (21,097.5 m) for men is __a__ s.

The record time for a half marathon (21,097.5 m) for women is __b__ s.
worksheet.commonFeedback:
Here is the function and script:

 

function [slope,intercept,halfmarathon] = TrackTimes(x,y,label)
clc,clf
disp(label)
logx=log10(x);logy=log10(y);
a=polyfit(logx,logy,1);
slope=a(1);
intercept=10^a(2);
xp=[min(x):max(x)];
yp=intercept*xp.^slope;
subplot(2,1,1)
loglog(x,y,'o',xp,yp)
xlabel='log10(x)';ylabel='log10(y)';title(label)
subplot(2,1,2)
plot(x,y,'o',xp,yp)
xlabel='x';ylabel='y';
halfmarathon=intercept*21097.5^slope;
end

format short g, format compact
xm=[100 200 400 800 1000  1500  2000  5000  10000 20000 42195];
tm=[9.58  19.19 43.18 100.9 131.96  206 284.79  757.4 1577.53 3386  7377];
[slope,intercept,halfmarathon] = TrackTimes(xm,tm,'Men:')
pause
